Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards

node.text:
Our latest print issue drops on September 15th! In anticipation, we’re revisiting the awe-inspiring home that graced the cover of our September/October 2020 issue—and also claimed Runner-Up and Community Pick for best bathroom in the 2020 Dwell Design Awards.
Square House by New York City architecture studio @levenbetts is surely more sanctuary than ruin, but it walks a beautiful line between the two. For the owners, the guesthouse was about designing a vestige 500 years into the future and working backward to a functional home. Several years of dialogue—steered by that idea of design from the future—led to a quietly monolithic concrete box set in a contemplative landscape of rocks and moss. The connection to the outdoors is one of the home’s most astounding characteristics. Although it reads as a single story, the floor level rises and lowers with the site’s topography, intentionally altering your perspective as you progress through the house. “When you’re in the sunken living room, you’re lower than the ground plane and you see nature at a very different scale,” says Stella Betts, cofounder of Levenbetts. “It’s an idea of porosity, or being out in nature and then entering every room in the house from wherever.” Take the full tour of Square House when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.
–
Photos by @edeani
Story by Sheila Kim
Structural Engineering by @silman.structural
Landscape Design by @markpeterkeane

This home is so energy efficient that the family living in it, a young couple and their two children, required no additional heating last winter. To build in Barcelona’s L’Ametlla del Vallès, the couple partnered with local architects @slowstudio.es, a firm renowned for designing and constructing houses with reduced energy consumption. "We decided to allocate a main part of the budget to the passive functioning of the house, investing in materials that would provide us with environmental quality and energy efficiency," says Jade Serra (@jade_slowstudio), partner and cofounder of the firm. “In this case, we worked with a thermal buffer: the patio greenhouse.” Separating the bedrooms from the common spaces, a glass-covered courtyard runs through the center of the home and creates a greenhouse effect, mediating the 1,340-square-foot home’s climate. “The result is an economical, natural system that is as—or more—efficient than controlled mechanical ventilation." Take the full tour of Carlo and Martí’s home at the link in bio.

This Costa Rican home, sitting on a forested, remote plot two hours from San José, was designed with spiritual transcendence in mind—along with off-grid sustainability. When architect María de la Paz Alice of @mazpazz_arquitectura first saw the site in the mountains of Palmichal de Acosta, she was skeptical due to its inaccessibility. Luckily for the client—a film producer and ocean conservationist who dreamed of a place where she could disconnect—Alice was game to take on the project. The home is called Casa Salvaje, or Wild House, an entirely autonomous and self-sustaining stone-and-concrete home that uses geometric openings to frame its tranquil surroundings. Teaming up with interior designer Ileana Guerrero—who worked with local artisans to craft custom furnishings for the living spaces—and landscape designer Jorge Salgado, the project is a breathtaking example of architecture that connects to the earth. The home’s entrance, which the architect refers to as “the vortex,” takes the form of a concrete cube with two prominent circular openings. Crystals encrusted in the floor capture and reflect the light that passes through the overhead oculus from the sun and moon. “As you walk in, the circular window framing the mountain view is the focal point, and the sky window above immediately connects you to your surroundings,” says the architect. "In every project, I try to provide at least one space that promotes a transcendental experience. I strive to create spaces that will benefit and expand people emotionally and spiritually, just as much as they do aesthetically." Take a walk through the inspiring escape at the link in bio.

After 14 years in a cramped, dimly lit apartment, a couple felt the need to head somewhere new. Once Irene Glezos and Julie Chartoff started searching for a new home, however, they quickly found that nothing in the market was a match for the period details and important memories of their current space: It was the home where they’d raised their first child, Max, who had passed. Instead of forcing the change of scenery, the couple turned to local architecture firm @worrellyeung to transform their 1,600-square-foot loft into an open, light-filled home with an additional bedroom and bathroom. Worrel Yeung’s co-founders, Max Worrell (@worrellmax) and Jejon Yeung (@mjejon), made the first move of taking out existing walls to open the space while allowing the visibility of historic windows, original plaster molding, and an industrial steel structure. The intervention, along with use of various structural elements, allowed the apartment to be organized as one large space that strikes the perfect balance between gathering areas and partitioned rooms. In addition to meeting the family’s needs, the renovation created a home that feels distinctly personal. A quiet material palette of ash wood elements, bone-white floors, monolithic gray pieces, and calming marble and stone elevates Irene and Julie's vast assortment of art, objects, and books. "The clients had some unique and fun requests such as crawling-height sleeping lofts, bookcase stairs, sprinkler pipes painted pink, a blue sink. But we listened," Yeung says. "It was a journey and mutual goal to see how playful we could be while keeping it sophisticated and timeless." Head to the link in bio to take the full tour of the Broadway Loft.

When this space-age prefab was discovered in South Africa, it had smashed windows and was without a front door. “Workers were knocking down a building nearby and we thought they were going to tear it down too,” says artist @craigbarnes_, who has since repaired the supernatural specimen. “It was a wreck. We found out who owned it, and on an impulse while on top of Table Mountain, we agreed to buy it.” The home’s history is just as exciting as Craig’s discovery. In 1965, Finnish designer Matti Suuronen set out to create an après-ski cabin that would be efficient to heat and easy to transport, giving rise to the Futuro home—truly a product of the Space Age with its sleek, UFO-like shape. Though it was marketed as a prefabricated tiny home suitable for the masses, fewer than 100 Futuro pods were made, with an estimated 60 still in existence. After a long process of coordinating logistics and timing, this Futuro house touched down in Somerset’s Marston Park in England, now offering guests a unique chance to savor an unusual slice of architectural history. To take the full tour of the Futuro House, head to the link in bio.

While designing a home on a secluded plateau in Valle de Bravo, architect Fernanda Canales (@fernandacanales_arquitectura) knew the isolated location and temperamental weather would be a challenge: not only would the house need to be resilient enough to withstand weather whiplash, but it also had to create all of its own energy. Instead of pulling away from the challenges, Fernanda leaned into them, crafting a self-sufficient home around four courtyards that embrace the surroundings through landscape views and varying solar exposure. Within the courtyards, native landscaping furthers this indoor/outdoor connection, in addition to a green roof overhead. “Since the house is only one level, it almost disappears into the landscape,” notes the architect, who says that’s one of her favorite aspects of the weekend home. Hit the link in bio to see the full tour of Casa Terreno.

This contemporary farmhouse outside Toronto makes its own rules. “People may not think of modern architecture and barn buildings as being similar, but for me, they are,” says @scottposno, speaking to the thought process behind his sleek-meets-rustic design. “Both types of buildings are stripped down to the basics, without ornament or frivolous details.” Indeed, modern and farmhouse architecture are commonly thought to be on two separate ends of the design spectrum: where one is sharp, the other is soft. One defines newness while the other is known for its beauty with age. This residence, however, is a perfect example of a happy medium. “Approaching a house design project with an open mind can yield great results," Posno says, reflecting on the 4,000-square-foot home and the two years it took to complete. After an unexpected breakup, Tiffany Jen (@jiffyten) found respite in this Catskills cabin with a village of her designer friends. When Tiffany— a Brooklyn-based designer and motion graphics artist—found this Catskills home on Zillow, it had been listed for some 350 days. “That was not a great sign,” she admits. After more than 100 tours and three failed offers in the search for that “dream cabin in the woods,” Tiffany and her then-partner committed. The problem came during the closing process, when the couple split up unexpectedly, turning the shared dream and investment into a solo endeavor. Luckily, Tiffany was able to lean on loved ones for guidance. Her father, an architect, helped her draft plans, recommended fixes, and advised on budget, while an interior designer friend came through with renderings of interior concepts. Another pal, a designer and woodworker, constructed the new stairs and built-in furniture. “I just felt really fortunate to have all of this support and help from my friends in the architecture world,” says the new homeowner. As for the personal touches, Tiffany says she is “very much inspired by Memphis design.” Starting with a neutral palette that brightened each space, she peppered every room with fun colors and uniquely shaped furniture. The walls are dotted with Tiffany’s and her friends’ art, along with unexpected color accents like the coral dining room table that she got off of Facebook Marketplace in exchange for a $20 plant. Once the cabin was complete, Tiffany hosted a massive sleepover to thank everyone for their support and to celebrate the complete transformation. “It was a very emotional moment,” she says, as they reflect on the days after closing when she was still sleeping on the floor. Take the full tour of Tiffany’s fresh cabin in the Catskills—dubbed Casa Magda—when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

In relocating from New Mexico to Oaxaca, a retired couple set their sights on a roughly 3,200-square-foot plot of land. With the help of architecture firm @espacio18, the couple erected Nuestro Sueño—“Our Dream”—a courtyard design with a concrete-and-brick materiality that draws on local vernacular. “Our responsibility was to show Elizabeth and Ray how to make a whole new way of life—accepting new typologies, new materials, and most importantly, to embrace the interior,” says architect Mario Ávila, codirector of Espacio 18. Taking the form of a rectangular box, the three-story home is organized around a central courtyard space that’s wide open to the sky. Although the home’s brick facade has a stoic nature, folding steel bay windows on the ground floor, along with open-air corridors and patios above, create interior spaces that welcome in the elements and create a convivial atmosphere for guests. Wood accents in the casework, ceiling beams, and furnishings also help to warm up the spaces, resulting in an inspired mix of traditional materials and forms with a modern twist. Architect Carla Osorio tops it off: "It’s a place where friends and mezcal won’t ever be missing." Take the full tour of the couple’s dream home come to life, and it’s impressive courtyards, at the link in bio.

“This house is an act of preservation,” says Jen Lowe, the director of interior design studio @ohlostudio, of this midcentury renovation in City Beach, a modernist enclave in Perth. Our clients should be applauded for their decision to retain this modest dwelling.” Ohlo collaborated with @simonpendal_architect and landscape designer Steven Postmus of @capa_studio to execute a shared vision. “The idea was to play to the strengths of the existing architectural language and to integrate a material palette and sense of space that riffs on the expansive, sun-bleached, Western Australian landscape,” says Lowe. The cramped four-bedroom, one-bathroom home was converted into three bedrooms with two baths that are separated from the open-plan living areas by two wide, angular steps. To echo the surrounding landscape, the design team inserted a sand-colored concrete pathway that meanders through the entire home, from the front letterbox to the rotunda in the rear garden. The home’s connection to place is further enhanced through a collection of Western Australian artwork, which was curated by Ohlo Studio. The sculptural built-in plinths and ledges throughout the living spaces allow the clients’ to display a growing collection of art, organically filling the home and adding a rich layer of texture. The interior material palette is intentionally simple—think natural timber, concrete floors, white walls, and bespoke render finishes—offering a crisp backdrop to the artwork. The primary bedroom, for example, features sculptural timber joinery that wraps around the wall. The gardens further enhance the home’s connection to the coastal setting: a rotunda in the rear garden, alongside an outdoor shower, encourages a coastal lifestyle and—like the rest of the home—celebrates its unique setting. Difficult circumstances often produce impressive ingenuity. Last winter, Conrado, an Uruguayan living in London, got to follow through on a long-held dream, entirely remotely. For years, he’d wanted to build a vacation home on family property in the coastal town of Blancarena where he could gather with loved ones. After several Zoom meetings with prefab builder @ihouse.uy, a Montevideo-based firm, Conrado finally got the ball rolling. “[It] was unusual because of the distance between us,” admits Agustin Sica, a member of iHouse’s design team. But by adapting practices and technology that enhanced the experience of remote collaboration, iHouse was able to keep Conrado involved at every step. It also didn’t hurt that Conrado’s mother was able to serve as an in-person liaison, accompanying the firm to the project site. Designed to modernize the small, wooden cabins that are common in the area, Casa ZGZ is a single-level, black-clad cabin comprising two modules pushed together lengthwise. The first includes the spaces that require plumbing: bathrooms and kitchen. The second module houses two bedrooms, along with the living and dining areas. The cabin’s exterior gets its black color from a natural oil-like finish that protects the wood, a treatment that also makes the home "melt into the shadow of the trees" for added privacy. Floor-to-ceiling windows and decks at both the front and rear further immerse the home into its setting. In a production plant adjacent to their studio in Montevideo, iHouse constructed the prefab’s pieces, then toted them to the site where they could be installed efficiently with minimal impact to the local environment. "Conrado was thrilled when he saw the house for the first time," shares Sica. "I remember him saying ‘It’s better than the pictures!’” Take a look through Casa ZGZ at the link in bio.

After taking a trip to study micro home design in Tokyo, one architect takes to her own backyard to try her hand at it. Driven by the need for additional space, architect and designer Emma Pereira of @emmanuelle____ put together a $140,500 budget to build a 400-square-foot guesthouse/studio behind her home in Miami’s Buena Vista neighborhood. Atelier Lumi, as it’s called, is a white stucco-clad refuge where sunlight, texture, and form create a voluminous sense of calm and understated beauty inspired by the masterful design she’d seen in Japan. “The Japanese are innovators, using visual techniques to make tiny spaces appear roomier,” says Emma. “The concept is to take our own life story and enhance the good parts, while adding elements that speak to who we want to be.” For a full budget breakdown of @atelierlumi, try Dwell+ at the link in bio.
